SHAP Values and Random Forest¶

  • Motivation:

The purpose of this assignment is to use to use the SHAP Values on a calssifier supervised learning model in order to explain the models' results and compare them.

  • Resources:

      *Dataset on Loan Deafaults.
  *H2O Algorithms
  *Random Forest

  • Methods:

      *GLM and Random Forest
  *Creating Dummy Variables for the Random Forest Algorithm
  *Multicollinearity and Variable Importance for Variable Selection
  *SHAP Values
  • Objective:

Using the modified dataset of XYZ Loans with all the features created in the past assigment, modify the dataset so that it is suitable for a random forest model form the sklearn library and then calculate SHAP values to explain how the different variables affect the model performance.

Modeling for Variable Selection¶

The dataset has already gone through a thorough process of feature engineering but The dataset right now has 78 predictors and one target variable. This might be too many variables,lets try to limit the ammount of variables for our model so that the algorithm can perform faster and more efficiently.

Lets start by defining the features and target variables and the train and test sets and then running a GLM model.

Variable Importance¶

Another useful technique for variable selection is the variable importance metric in a tree based algorithm like random forest. The concept behind the Variable Importance measurement is that a variable importance is measured on how many times the variable is selected to split the nodes of the tree.

In [9]:

        keep_cross_validation_predictions=True,
        seed=1234,
        stopping_metric = "AUC")

The random forest algorithm has three important metrics that complement each other. The original measurement is called the relative importance and measures the importance of the variable in all the trees created. The scaled importance then scales this importance in comparison to the rest of the variables.

To select my variables then I will create a threshold were anything that has a scaled importance of below 10% will be rejected.

Cleaning the variables¶

Some variables have too many categories which makes it harder for the algorithm to grasp the contents of the variable and might make it work harder whihc in tunr gives it a false sense importance as the algorithm selects that variable just because splitting into so many catergories produces many different results.

In this particular dataset the variables MB007 (system) and AP005 (dates) have more than 5 categories. Lets fix that.

for k in range(len(data["MB007"])):
    var = re.split(r'(\d+)', data.loc[k,"MB007"])[0]
    if var == "WEB":
        data.loc[k,"MB007"] = 'PC'
    elif var == "IPHONE" or var == "IPAD" or var == "IPOD" or var == "APPLE" :
        data.loc[k,"MB007"] = 'APPLE'
    elif var == "SAMSUNG":
        data.loc[k,"MB007"] = 'SAMSUNG'
    elif var =="HUAWEI" or var =="OPPO" or var =="XIAOMI" or var =="MEIZU" or var =="HONOR" or var =="GIONEE" or var =="LEECO" or var =="ZTE" or var =="NUBIA" or var =="ASUS":
        data.loc[k,"MB007"] = 'ANDROID_ASIA'
    elif var == "Noinfo":
        data.loc[k,"MB007"] = 'Noinfo'
    elif var =="SONY" or var =="MOTOROLA" or var =="ONEPLUS" or var =="LENOVO" or var =="HTC" or var =="NOKIA" or var =="GOOGLE":
        data.loc[k,"MB007"] = 'ANDROID_BIG_BRAND'
    else:
        data.loc[k,"MB007"] = 'OTHER'

By combining values into a broader category I can reduce the categories and still not lose the predictive power of the variable.

Random Forest on sklearn¶

The random forest algorithm in the sklearn library requires some feature engineering for it to perform at its best. Categorical variables are not interpreted as categories by the algorithm and therefore have no predictive power on the model. To solve this problem, I will create dummy variables of each category of each categorical variable. That way the model will be able to interpret the categories.

In [19]:
#Hot encoding of categorical variables
cat_var = pd.DataFrame(pd.DataFrame(data[new_features].dtypes).iloc[:,0][pd.DataFrame(data[new_features].dtypes).iloc[:,0] == 'object']).index.tolist()
for i in range(len(cat_var)):
    if i != 0:
        temp_df = pd.get_dummies(data[cat_var[i]])
        temp_df.columns = [cat_var[i]+"_"+temp_df.columns.tolist()[j] for j in range(len(temp_df.columns.tolist()))]
        prev_df = pd.concat([prev_df, temp_df], axis=1)
    else:
        prev_df = pd.get_dummies(data[cat_var[i]])
        prev_df.columns = [cat_var[i]+"_"+prev_df.columns.tolist()[j] for j in range(len(prev_df.columns.tolist()))]
prev_df

SHAP Values¶

SHAP Values come from the Shapley value which can be defined as "the measurement of the average marginal contribution across all permutations of a model". The SHAP Value is then the measurment of the effect of each variable against the other and the model and its correlation be it negative or positive. Lets satrt by using the mean SHAP value to calculate the variable importance per class for each variable.

In [29]:
#shap values
shap_values = shap.TreeExplainer(clf).shap_values(X_train)
In [30]:
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_train, plot_type="bar")
  • TD013 seem so be the most important variable.
  • On our H2O Random forest algorithm the most important variables were Binned variables but for this algorithm binned variables were turned into dummy variables which makes it loose some of its predictive power as a whole.
  • The classes for each of the most important variables seem to be very well represented in the importance of the model.

  • Simplified Importance Variable

This graph shows a bit of a different representation of the variable importance plot. Here each variable's importance is plotted and the correlation of that variable to the target variable is expressed by the color of the bar where Red is a positive impact and blue is a negative impact.

In [112]:
def ABS_SHAP(df_shap,df):
    #import matplotlib as plt
    # Make a copy of the input data
    shap_v = pd.DataFrame(df_shap[0]).iloc[:,0:20]
    feature_list = df.iloc[:,0:20].columns
    shap_v.columns = feature_list
    df_v = df.copy().reset_index().drop('index',axis=1)
    
    # Determine the correlation in order to plot with different colors
    corr_list = list()
    for i in feature_list:
        b = np.corrcoef(shap_v[i],df_v[i])[1][0]
        corr_list.append(b)
    corr_df = pd.concat([pd.Series(feature_list),pd.Series(corr_list)],axis=1).fillna(0)
    # Make a data frame. Column 1 is the feature, and Column 2 is the correlation coefficient
    corr_df.columns  = ['Variable','Corr']
    corr_df['Sign'] = np.where(corr_df['Corr']>0,'red','blue')
    
    # Plot it
    shap_abs = np.abs(shap_v)
    k=pd.DataFrame(shap_abs.mean()).reset_index()
    k.columns = ['Variable','SHAP_abs']
    k2 = k.merge(corr_df,left_on = 'Variable',right_on='Variable',how='inner')
    k2 = k2.sort_values(by='SHAP_abs',ascending = True)
    colorlist = k2['Sign']
    ax = k2.plot.barh(x='Variable',y='SHAP_abs',color = colorlist, figsize=(20,20),legend=False)
    ax.set_xlabel("SHAP Value (Red = Positive Impact)")
    
ABS_SHAP(shap_values,X_train)

SHAP Plot for Observation Importance¶

Each observation provides a different output on the model based on the formula created for that model. Lets test out then how different observations can affect the model and how the variables push the output of the model in each case. A random selection of observations will be used here to show the results.

In [141]:
shap.initjs()

# Write in a function
def shap_plot(j):
    X_output = X_test.copy()
    X_output.loc[:,'predict'] = np.round(clf.predict(X_output),2)

    # Randomly pick some observations
    random_picks = np.arange(1,330,50) # Every 50 rows
    S = X_output.iloc[random_picks]
    explainerModel = shap.TreeExplainer(clf)
    shap_values_Model = explainerModel.shap_values(S)
    p = shap.force_plot(base_value=explainerModel.expected_value[0], shap_values=shap_values_Model[0][j,:], features=S.iloc[j,:])
    
    return(p)

Conclusion¶

The SHAP Values and all the tools that the shap library offers help us see the impact of each observation on the model and how it affects the perfromance of the model. Here we can see that the most important variables TD013, AP003 and TD009 are always amongst the variables that have most impact for each observation. That means that the values that these variables have greatly affect the prediction of the model. When evaluating a model like this in a real life scenario this would be of great help. Further explanation into the nature of the variable and where it comes from could proivide a deeper understanding as to why customers who have these characteristics default or don't default on a loan.
